snippet.title: LearnNext Class 8 Geography l Resources l Human-Made And Human Resources
snippet.description:
Human-made resources are resources that are obtained by modifying natural resources like Iron, steel and aluminium.

Technology, knowledge and skill are used to convert natural resources into usable forms and hence are called as Human-made resources as well. People with their knowledge and skill have invented technologies to make the best possible use of resources.

People are a special resource. They are called human resources. Human resources are the most important asset of a nation. For a nation to be prosperous, its human resources must be healthy and knowledgeable.

Effective human resource development programs must be planned for:
Providing education and vocational training to everyone and
Improving the quality of life by providing basic health care facilities.

Human Resource Development helps people develop their skills, knowledge and abilities so that they are able to create more resources.

snippet.title: Materials - Metals and Non-Metals - Science - Class 8
snippet.description:
Metals are used in making machinery, automobiles, airplanes, buildings, trains, satellites, gadgets, cooking utensils, water boilers, etc.
Sodium and potassium are soft metals that can be cut with a knife.  Mercury is a liquid metal.

The metal base in an electric iron is for conducting heat, not electricity. Metals are very good conductors of heat, too. That's why cooking utensils, irons, heaters, etc. are all made of metals.
Metals can be easily shaped into wires. This property of metals is called ductility.
Metals can be easily shaped into thin flat sheets. This characteristic of metals is called malleability.
Metals make a sound when struck with hard objects. Metals can be polished to a shiny appearance. That's why gold and silver jewelry shine so much. Read more at http://learnnext.com/lesson/CBSE-VIII-Science-Physical-Metals.htm

snippet.title: Force and Pressure - Force - Science - Class 8
snippet.description:
Force is a kind of push or a pull on an object. The interaction of one object with another results in a force between the two objects. If a force acts on an object in the direction of its motion, then the object moves faster. If a force acts on an object opposite to the direction of its motion, then the objects slows down. Force may also change the direction of motion of an object. The effect of force changes with the direction of its application. Forces acting on an object in the same direction add to each other, while forces acting opposite to each other results in the difference of the forces. Read more at http://learnnext.com/lesson/CBSE-VIII-Science-Force8.htm

snippet.title: Cell - Structure and Functions - Introduction to Cells - Science - Class 8
snippet.description:
In this video you'll learn about Structure and Functions of Cell

With the help of a microscope, an English scientist, Robert Hooke, first discovered the existence of cells in 1665.Scanning electron microscopes are used to examine the external parts of various organisms.The transmission electron microscope is used to view the internal structure of a cell and its organelles.

Unicellular Organisms- Organisms that are made up of a single cell and perform all their vital activities, like reproduction, locomotion and digestion, are called unicellular organisms.

Multi-Cellular Organisms- Organisms that are made up of more than one cell are called multi-cellular organisms.

Amoeba uses small finger-like projections called pseudopodia for locomotion and to capture prey.Paramecium is a single cell and is built in such a way that it performs all its vital activities, like reproduction, locomotion, digestion, and so on. snippet.title: Understanding Quadrilaterals - Polygons - Maths - Class 8
snippet.description:
We know a polygon is a simple closed figure made up of only line segments.  We can classify polygons according to the number of sides or vertices.
The simple polygon we know is a triangle. A triangle has three sides and, thus, is a three-sided polygon.
A four-sided polygon is called a quadrilateral. 
A five sided polygon is called a pentagon.
In this manner, we can obtain a six-sided polygon called a hexagon, a seven-sided polygon, called a heptagon, and so on. Read more at https://learnnext.com/lesson/CBSE-VIII-Maths-Polygons.htm

snippet.title: Class 8 | Science | Friction | Frictions and its types
snippet.description:
Class 8 | Science | Friction | Frictions and its types

In this module, you will learn about friction and identify the factors affecting friction.
Why do we rub our hands in cold weather?
Rubbing our hands together makes us feel warmer. 
When we rub our palms together, there is friction between the surfaces of our palms. That gives us warmth.
Basically, friction is a force that opposes the relative motion between two objects in contact.

Friction produces heat between the surfaces of the two objects that are in contact and in relative motion.

That’s why we feel warmer when we rub our hands together. 
Friction exists between two surfaces due to 
• Irregular or uneven surfaces,
• The interlocking of micro-level  irregularities of two surfaces 
• Ploughing of harder surfaces into  smoother surfaces

Friction also causes wear and tear of parts in machinery or even in the sole of our shoes.
The holes in the sole of our shoe are a result of friction between the sole and the roads that it comes in contact with.

snippet.title: Class 8 | Maths | Mensuration | Surface Area Of Solids
snippet.description:
Class 8 | Maths | Mensuration | Surface Area Of Solids

In this module, you will learn how to calculate the surface areas of cubes and cuboids.
The surface area of a solid is the sum of the areas of its faces.
For example, a cuboid is made up of six rectangular faces.
The surface area of a cuboid is equal to the sum of the areas of its six faces.
The opposite faces of a cuboid are identical.
Hence, its surface area will be equal to the sum of the areas of its six faces.
There are three pairs of identical faces in a cuboid.    Thus, there are three pairs of identical faces in a cuboid.
Now, let’s assume the length, breadth and height of the cuboid is l, b and h respectively.
Since, the faces are rectangular in shape, their areas will be equal to the product of their lengths and breadths.  

Let us calculate the area of each face.
They are:.. l into h...
...l into b
...b into h
...l into h
...l into b and...
...b into h respectively.

snippet.title: Class 8 | Science | Light | Reflection In Plane Mirrors
snippet.description:
Class 8 | Science | Light | Reflection In Plane Mirrors

In this module, you will learn to identify the laws of reflection.
How are we able to see objects around us?
James: Hey, Tina! Look here!

Tina: Ouch! What are you doing? Stop that! 
Objects around us are visible only when light emitted or reflected from them enters our eyes.
Miss Sunshine: I see you’re having a good time! 

James: Yeah! This mirror game is cool!

Miss Sunshine: Sure it is! However, do you know that 
We all have played with a mirror, trying to reflect light on someone. 
this game uses the phenomenon -of reflection of light.?
Tina: Well, I can definitely see he is using sunlight to tease me. 

So, What exactly is a reflection of light?
Miss Sunshine: The bouncing back of light incident on an object, into the same medium through which it is incident on the object, is called a reflection of light.
James: Bouncing back of light?
Miss Sunshine: Sounds confusing? Well, let's me start with the basics. 
WeYou are aware that light travels in straight lines., right?
James: Yes, we learned that in school.
Miss. Sunshine: The path along which light travels is called a ray of light. A ray of light is generally represented by a directed line segment. A collection of light rays is called a beam of light.

snippet.title: Class 8 | Science | Reproduction in animals | Oviparous and Viviparous Animals
snippet.description:
Class 8 | Science | Reproduction in animals | Oviparous and Viviparous Animals

In this module, you will learn about viviparous  and oviparous  animals.

What are viviparous and oviparous animals?
Animals that directly give birth to young ones are called viviparous animals. 
Some of the examples of viviparous animals include human beings, cats, dogs and horses.
Examples of oviparous animals include hens, frogs, fish, lizards and butterflies.

What type of fertilization  takes place in viviparous and oviparous animals?
Viviparous animals, such as humans, cows, dogs and horses, undergo internal fertilization.
On the other hand, oviparous animals, such as frogs, lizards, fish and butterflies, generally undergo external fertilization.
However, there are exceptions.
For example, some species of fish, such as skates, undergo internal fertilization, but lay the eggs outside the body.
This characteristic makes them oviparous, which undergo internal fertilization.
Another exception is hen.
The hen also undergoes internal fertilization, though it is an oviparous animal.
